'''Curanilahue''' ({{IPA-es|kuɾaniˈlawe}}) is a [[Chile]]an [[Communes of Chile|commune]] and [[List of cities in Chile|city]] in [[Arauco Province]], [[Biobío Region]].
==Demographics== According to the 2002 [[census]] of the [[National Statistics Institute (Chile)|National Statistics Institute]], Curanilahue spans an area of {{convert|994.3|sqkm|0|abbr=on}} and has 31,943 inhabitants (16,115 men and 15,828 women). Of these, 30,126 (94.3%) lived in [[urban area]]s and 1,817 (5.7%) in [[rural area]]s. Between the 1992 and 2002 censuses, the population fell by 5% (1,688 persons).<ref name= "INE"/>
==Administration== As a commune, Curanilahue is a third-level [[administrative division of Chile]] administered by a [[municipal council]], headed by an [[alcalde]] who is directly elected every four years. The 2013-2016 alcalde is Luis Gengnagel .<ref name="Munitel"/><ref name="Official"/>
Within the [[electoral divisions of Chile]], Curanilahue is represented in the [[Chamber of Deputies of Chile|Chamber of Deputies]] by Manuel Monsalve ([[Socialist Party of Chile|PS]]) and Iván Norambuena ([[Independent Democratic Union|UDI]]) as part of the 46th electoral district, (together with [[Lota, Chile|Lota]], [[Lebu, Chile|Lebu]], [[Arauco, Chile|Arauco]], [[Los Álamos]], [[Cañete, Chile|Cañete]], [[Contulmo]] and [[Tirúa]]). The commune is represented in the [[Senate of Chile|Senate]] by Victor Pérez Varela (UDI) and Mariano Ruiz -Esquide Jara (PDC) as part of the 13th senatorial constituency (Biobío-Coast).
